Object.Object: Merging two concetps where both concepts are unreviewed (status='R').
Merging two concepts that were released previously in different CUIs.
Merging two concepts where both contain releasable atoms from the same source and the source is in ic_single.
Merging two concepts where one contains releasable atoms from some source A, and the other contains releasable atoms from source B and sources A and B are listed in ic_pair.
Merging two concepts where both contain current-version MSH atoms.
Merging different rels to MSH MH
Merging two concepts that contain different releasable relationships to the same latest version MSH MH.
Merging two concepts connected by a releasable, approved, non RT?, SY, LK, SFO/LFO, BT?, or NT?, current version MSH relationship.
Merging two concepts where one contains a previous version MSH MH and the other contains a releasable, latest version MSH atom and their codes are different.
Merging two concepts that contain releasable current-version MSH atoms with different MUI values.
Merging across MSH codes (D-D, Q-Q, D-Q, Q-C)

Merging two concepts where both contain releasable current version MSH atoms with different codes, specifically (D-D, Q-Q, D-Q, Q-C). However, D-Q may exist together if the D has termgroup EN, EP, or MH and the Q has termgroup GQ.
Merging two concepts both containing releasable, current version MSH atoms with different codes. Specifically (D-C, C-C).
Merging two concepts that both contain releasable atoms from the same source but different codes and that source is listed in ic_single. Typically the MGV_B and MGV_I lists should be disjoint.
Merging two concepts that contain releasable atoms across sources (usually previous and update versions of same source) but different codes where these sources are listed in ic_pair.

Merging two concepts in such a way to produce an MGV_J violation, unless the merge will not increase the distinct code count in the target concept. In other words, if all of the codes from the source concept atoms appear already in the target concept, there is not violation.
Merging two concepts in which one contains one object (STY,source,termgroup) and the other contains an incompatible object as listed in ic_pair.
Merging two concepts that contain releasable "NEC" atoms with different sources.
Merging two concepts that both contain releasable MTH/PN atoms.
Merging two concepts that both contain releasable MTH/MM atoms.
Splitting a concept containing atoms with the same last_release_cui
Merging two concepts where one contains a releasable, current version MDR atom and the other has a chemical semantic type.
Merging two concepts connected by an approved, releasable, non RT?, SY, LK, SFO/LFO, BT?, or NT? relationship whose source is not MSH and is not listed in ic_single.
